            <fr:title text="Unitary Invariant Matrix Norm">Unitary Invariant Matrix Norm</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>
Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}\in \mathbb {R}^{m\times  n}.]]></fr:tex> We say the matrix norm is unitary invariant if <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\left ||\mathbf {A}\right ||_{\sharp }\ =\ \left ||\mathbf {PAQ}\right ||_{\sharp },\quad \forall \ \mathbf {P}\in  O(m),\ \mathbf {Q}\in  O(n).]]></fr:tex></html:p>
            <html:p>The two most common examples are both unitary invariant because they depend on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}]]></fr:tex> only through its singular values: the <fr:link href="/3U43/" title="Spectral norm" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/3U43/" display-uri="3U43" type="local">Spectral norm</fr:link> (<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\|\sigma (\mathbf {A})\|_\infty ]]></fr:tex>) and the <fr:link href="/4M9J/" title="Frobenius norm" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/4M9J/" display-uri="4M9J" type="local">Frobenius norm</fr:link> (<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\|\sigma (\mathbf {A})\|_2]]></fr:tex>).</html:p>
